  "prompt": "Will 8 RAC tickets that have changed to CNF, get adjacent berths?",
  "response": "When **8 RAC (Reservation Against Cancellation)** tickets are **confirmed (CNF)**, it means that the passengers will be allotted confirmed berths. However, whether these berths will be adjacent or not depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Availability of berths**: If there are 8 adjacent berths available in the same coach, the passengers may get adjacent berths. However, if the berths are scattered across different coaches or compartments, they may not be adjacent.\n\n2. **Booking details**: If the 8 RAC tickets were booked together as a single group, the Indian Railways system usually tries to allot adjacent berths, but it\u2019s not guaranteed.\n\n3. **Last-minute cancellations**: If your tickets were confirmed due to last-minute cancellations, the berths may already be scattered, and it\u2019s less likely they\u2019ll be adjacent.\n\n4. **Train and coach configuration**: In some trains, only certain coaches or sections have adjacent berths, which may not match the number of confirmed tickets.\n\n### Key Points:\n- **RAC to CNF** ensures a confirmed berth, but adjacency is not guaranteed.\n- The railway system tries to accommodate groups together, but it\u2019s subject to availability.\n- You can check your berth allocation on the **PNR status** or **charting details** before boarding.\n\nIf adjacent berths are crucial, you can try requesting other passengers to swap seats once on the train, depending on their willingness.",
